AB  - The dynamic scheduling of automated container terminals has emerged as a critical challenge in port operations optimization. This study addresses two persistent issues in port transport equipment scheduling: operational uncertainties and chronic congestion at cargo interfaces. We propose a novel reinforcement learning framework that innovatively integrates Multi-Input Multi-Output (MIMO) communication theory into port logistics optimization. The methodology comprises three key components: 1) Development of an isomorphic mapping model that establishes precise correspondence between port logistics elements and communication system components, 2) Implementation of an enhanced Q-learning algorithm with multi-dimensional state-action space configuration, and 3) Deployment of a digital twin platform for virtual-real interaction verification of scheduling policies. Through extensive simulations on a validated terminal model, the proposed framework demonstrates superior performance metrics: achieving a 16% reduction in average task completion time while decreasing quay crane waiting time variability by 31% compared to conventional heuristic approaches. Notably, the MIMO-inspired real-time scheduling mechanism reduces peak-period congestion occurrences by 47% through intelligent resource multiplexing. These empirical results substantiate the framework's capability to enhance horizontal transportation efficiency while maintaining operational stability under stochastic disturbances. © 2025 IEEE.
